Preterm Birth Detection using electrohysteography¶

Sohaib Zafar and Sanna Herrala

Task:¶

  • Use EHG data from 39 women to build a classifier for predicting pre-term birth
  • Differentiate the EHG signals into two classes: 1 for the mothers that gave preterm birth and 0 for the mothers with normal pregnancy
  • Train 2 classifiers and compare how well they do

def getSignalLength(df):
  sigLength = len(df['s1'].to_numpy())
  return sigLength

def getTimeInSeconds(df):
  length = getSignalLength(df)
  seconds = np.linspace(0, length/fs, length)
  return seconds

Fourier transform and filtering¶

In [6]:
# Setting up the functions for transforming and filtering the data


# using Fourier transform to transform the data into the frequency domain

def fourierTransform(dataArray):
  transformedDataArray = []
  for [i, j] in enumerate (dataArray):
    S1 = dataArray[i]['s1']
    S2 = dataArray[i]['s2']
    S3 = dataArray[i]['s3']
    
    sigLength = len(S1.to_numpy())
    #fx = fft.rfftfreq(sigLength, 1/fs)
    fyS1 = fft.rfft(S1.values)
    fyS2 = fft.rfft(S2.values)
    fyS3 = fft.rfft(S3.values)
    #data = {'fx':fx, 's1':fyS1, 's2':fyS2,'s3':fyS3}
    data = {'s1':fyS1, 's2':fyS2,'s3':fyS3}

    df = pd.DataFrame(data)
    transformedDataArray.append(df)
  return transformedDataArray

# setting up a high-pass Butterworth filter to apply to the signals
# the filtering frequency was chosen by plotting different options
# and choosing the best looknig one
highcut = 0.05
order = 5
fs = 20
nyq = 0.5 * fs
high = highcut/nyq
b,a = signal.butter(order, high, btype='high', analog=False)

def filterSignalData(dataArray):
  filteredDataArray = []
  for [i,j] in enumerate (dataArray):
    signalS1 = dataArray[i]['s1']
    signalS2 = dataArray[i]['s2']
    signalS3 = dataArray[i]['s3']

    filteredS1 = signal.filtfilt(b,a, signalS1)
    filteredS2 = signal.filtfilt(b,a, signalS2)
    filteredS3 = signal.filtfilt(b,a, signalS3)
    data = {'s1':filteredS1,'s2': filteredS2, 's3':filteredS3}
    df = pd.DataFrame(data)
    filteredDataArray.append(df)
  return filteredDataArray


# an inverse Fourier trandform function to transform data
# from frequency to time domain 
def inverseFourierTransform(dataArray):
  transformedDataArray = []
  for [i, j] in enumerate (dataArray):
    S1 = dataArray[i]['s1']
    S2 = dataArray[i]['s2']
    S3 = dataArray[i]['s3']
    
    sigLength = len(S1.to_numpy())
   
    fyS1 = fft.ifft(S1.values)
    fyS2 = fft.ifft(S2.values)
    fyS3 = fft.ifft(S3.values)
    data = {'s1':fyS1, 's2':fyS2,'s3':fyS3}
    df = pd.DataFrame(data)
    transformedDataArray.append(df)
  return transformedDataArray

# processing the data in different ways to find out what produces the best looking result


# Fourier transform the original signal
ftDataNormal = fourierTransform(normalData)
ftDataPreterm = fourierTransform(pretermData)

# Filter original data after Fourer transform
filteredFtDataNormal = filterSignalData(ftDataNormal)
filteredFtDataPreterm = filterSignalData(ftDataPreterm)

# Apply inverse Fourier transform to data after Fourier transform and filtering
inverseFilteredFtDataNormal = inverseFourierTransform(filteredFtDataNormal)
inverseFilteredFtDataPreterm = inverseFourierTransform(filteredFtDataPreterm)

# Filter the original data before a transform
filteredNormal = filterSignalData(normalData)
filteredPreterm = filterSignalData(pretermData)

# Fourier transform the filtered original data
ftFilteredNormal = fourierTransform(filteredNormal)
ftFilteredPreterm = fourierTransform(filteredPreterm)

Feature extraction¶

Features are extracted both in the time and frequency domain. This blog post by Matteo Gambera (2021) was used to determine what features to extract and how.

In [10]:
#function to extract time domain features
#the loop will go over the s1, s2 and s3 columns in that order
#the features are compiled in a list and added to a pandas dataframe

def extract_time_features(timeData, label, id_val):
  featureArray = []
  featureArray.append(id_val)
  featureArray.append(label)
  for column in timeData[1:]:  
    signal = timeData[column] 
    mean = np.mean(signal)
    std = np.std(signal)
    variance = np.var(signal)
    median = np.median(signal)
    iqr = stats.iqr(signal)
    skewness = stats.skew(signal)
    kurtosis = stats.kurtosis(signal)
    ptp_range = np.ptp(signal)
    rms = np.sqrt(np.mean(signal**2))
    power = np.mean(signal**2)
    peak = np.max(np.abs(signal))
    crest_factor = peak/rms
    form_factor = rms/mean
    pulse_indicator = peak/mean
     
    features = [mean, std, variance, median, iqr, skewness, kurtosis, ptp_range, 
                rms, power, peak, crest_factor, form_factor, pulse_indicator]
    
    for i in features:
        featureArray.append(i)
  
  return featureArray

# function to extract frequency domain features, similar to the time domain one
def extract_frequency_features(frequencyData, id_val):
    featureArray = []
    featureArray.append(id_val)
    for column in frequencyData:
        S = np.abs(frequencyData[column]**2)/len(frequencyData[column])
        max_f = np.max(S)
        sum_f = np.sum(S)
        mean_f = np.mean(S)
        var_f = np.var(S)
        peak_f = np.max(np.abs(S))
        features = [max_f, sum_f, mean_f, var_f, peak_f]
        for i in features:
            featureArray.append(i)
    return featureArray

# functions for looping through the arrays that hold the signal data
# that add the extracted features to dataframes
def getTimeFeatures(dataArray, label, id_start):
    id_val = id_start
    for [i,j] in enumerate (dataArray):
        signal_features = extract_time_features(dataArray[i], label, id_val)
        timeFeatures.loc[len(timeFeatures)]=signal_features
        id_val += 1

def getFrequencyFeatures(dataArray, id_start):
    id_val = id_start
    for [i,j] in enumerate (dataArray):
        signal_features = extract_frequency_features(dataArray[i], id_val)
        frequencyFeatures.loc[len(frequencyFeatures)]=signal_features
        id_val += 1

Training a model using k-nearest neighbors¶

In [15]:
# setting up a function for training and scoring a knn classifier
def knn_maker_and_scorer(n, scaled_features_train, labels_train, scaled_features_test):
  knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n)
  knn.fit(scaled_features_train, labels_train)
  predictions = knn.predict(scaled_features_test)

  accuracy_score = metrics.accuracy_score(labels_test, predictions)
  confusion_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(labels_test, predictions)
  classification_report = metrics.classification_report(labels_test, predictions)

  print("Accuracy Score: ",accuracy_score,"\n")
  print("Confusion Matrix: \n", confusion_matrix, "\n")
  print("Classification Report: \n", classification_report)

  metrics.plot_confusion_matrix(knn, scaled_features_test, labels_test, cmap='Greens')
  plt.show()

Tuning knn¶

With k = 3 the classifier has an accuracy of approx. 58%. To increase the accuracy we need to tune the parameter k. As we only have 39 samples it makes sense to use leave-one-out cross validation to ensure that the training set is as big as possible.

In [17]:
# need to first scale all of the features
scaler=StandardScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(features)


# setting up a grid search to find optimal k
# the model is evaluated for k = 1...30
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
grid = GridSearchCV(knn, dict(n_neighbors=list(range(1, 30))) , cv=LeaveOneOut(), scoring='accuracy')
grid_search = grid.fit(scaled_features, labels)
print("Best k value: ",grid_search.best_params_)
print("Best accuracy score: ",grid_search.best_score_)

Best k value:  {'n_neighbors': 2}
Best accuracy score:  0.6153846153846154

A single model with k=2 and the 30/70 data split did as well as the k=3 model did. Even with an optimized k value there is not enough data after a split to train a good model.

0.6153846153846154

The mean accuracy score produced by the cross validation is the same as the one from grid search, which makes sense because we also had grid search set to perform leave-one-out cross validation.

Conclusion¶

Comparing the models¶

None of the three models performed particularly well. K neares neighbors did the bes, but even that only had accuracies of about 60% at best. Naive Bayes and decision tree produced worse results than if one were to guess at random.

Ways to improve the results¶

  • More data
  • a more sophisticated filtering method
  • could try leaving out the first ~minute of data to decrease the impact of the initial climb
  • feature extraction using tsfel or tsfresh woulf give us more features and evaluate their usefullness automatically
    • we tried to use them, but it was too slow
  • better feature selection
    • we tried to see how the model performed if we left ou some of the features, but the performance was worse
